"1391":"1391","1425":"1425","about 1417":"omkring 1417","1423":"1423","1478":"1478","1420":"1420","about 1425":"omkring 1425","1375":"1375","about 1420":"omkring 1420","1419":"1419","about 1395":"omkring 1395","Wraxall Manor, South Wraxall, Wiltshire, England":"South Wraxall, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom","Wiltshire, England":"Wiltshire, England","England":"England","South Wraxall, Wiltshire, England":"South Wraxall, Wiltshire, England"},"nl":{"about 1395–about 1425":"circa 1395–circa 1425","1395–1425":"1395–1425","1391–1425":"1391–1425","1419–1478":"1419–1478","1420–1490":"1420–1490","1423–1490":"1423–1490","1375–Male":"1375–Overleden","1375–Female":"1375–Overleden","1395":"1395","1490":"1490","1391":"1391","1425":"1425","about 1417":"circa 1417","1423":"1423","1478":"1478","1420":"1420","about 1425":"circa 1425","1375":"1375","about 1420":"circa 1420","1419":"1419","about 1395":"circa 1395","Wraxall Manor, South Wraxall, Wiltshire, England":"South Wraxall, Wiltshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Wiltshire, England":"Wiltshire, England","England":"England","South Wraxall, Wiltshire, England":"South Wraxall, Wiltshire, England"},"en":{"about 1395–about 1425":"about 1395–about 1425","1395–1425":"1395–1425","1391–1425":"1391–1425","1419–1478":"1419–1478","1420–1490":"1420–1490","1423–1490":"1423–1490","1375–Male":"1375–Deceased","1375–Female":"1375–Deceased","1395":"1395","1490":"1490","1391":"1391","1425":"1425","about 1417":"about 1417","1423":"1423","1478":"1478","1420":"1420","about 1425":"about 1425","1375":"1375","about 1420":"about 1420","1419":"1419","about 1395":"about 1395","Wraxall Manor, South Wraxall, Wiltshire, England":"South Wraxall, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom","Wiltshire, England":"Wiltshire, England","England":"England","South Wraxall, Wiltshire, England":"South Wraxall, Wiltshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Godfrey","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): from the Norman personal name <i>Godefrei</i>, <i>Godefroi(s)</i>, composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>god</i>, <i>got</i> ‘god’ + <i>frid(u)</i>, <i>fred</i> ‘peace’. See also   Jeffrey  .","Irish: shortened and Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Gothraidh</b> or <b>Ó Gothraidh</b>, ‘descendant of <i>Gothfrith</i>’, an Old Norse personal name often Anglicized as <i>Godfrey</i>. Compare   McGorry  ,   McCaffrey  .","History: An Irish family of the name Godfrey originated in Romney, Kent. The first of them to settle in Ireland was Colonel John Godfrey, who was rewarded with lands in Kerry for his services in the 1641 rebellion. Godefroy, Lord of Normanville, from Normandy, was married in Trois-Rivières, QC, in 1636. He was captured by the Iroquois in 1652. His brother, Lord of Linctot, from Rouen, was also married in 1636 in Trois-Rivières, and lived from 1629 to 1632 among the Hurons. Another Godefroy, from Paris, was a trader and interpreter from 1623."],"variants":[{"name":"Geurts","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Florent, Jacques.","Dutch and Flemish: patronymic from a vernacular shortened form of the ancient Germanic personal names <i>Godevaard</i> (see   Godfrey  ) or <i>Godert</i> (see   Gotthardt  )."]},{"name":"Good","meanings":["English: nickname from Middle English <i>gode</i> ‘good’ (Old English <i>gōd</i>).","English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Gode</i>, representing either Old English <i>Goda</i> (male) or <i>Gode</i> (female), in part a byname and in part a short form of various compound names with the first element <i>gōd</i>, or perhaps a pet form of Old French names in <i>God-</i> such as   Godfrey  .","Americanized form (translation into English) of German   Gut   and   Guth  , or Dutch <b>Goed</b> and   Goede  ."]},{"name":"Goffredo","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Alfonso, Angelo, Carmine, Carolina, Marina, Mario, Nicola, Savino, Vito.","Italian: from the personal name <i>Goffredo</i>, an equivalent of   Godfrey  ."]},{"name":"Jeffrey","meanings":["English and Scottish: from the common Middle English and Older Scots personal name <i>Geffrey</i>, a borrowing of Old French <i>Geuffrei</i>, <i>Jeufrei</i>, <i>Jefrei</i>, <i>Gosfrei</i>, <i>Jofrei</i>. The principal source of the Old French forms was probably ancient Germanic <i>Gautfrid</i>, from an ethnic name + <i>frithu</i> ‘peace’. It was commonly Latinized in early documents as <i>Gaufridus</i> or <i>Galfridus</i>, but also as <i>Goisfridus</i> or <i>Gosfridus</i>. Anglo-Norman French <i>Jofreith</i>, <i>Jofrei</i> lies behind the English surnames <i>Joffrey</i> and <i>Joffray</i>, which are recorded in the late nineteenth century, but may now be extinct."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Lady Margaret Godfrey was born about 1395, in England, her father, Richard or Reginald Godfrey, was 11393 and her mother, Mrs Richard Godfrey, was 22. She married Sir Robert Longe about 1417, in Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 3 sons. She died about 1425, in Wiltshire, England, at the age of 32."},"et":{"about 1395–about 1425":"umbes 1395–umbes 1425","1395–1425":"1395–1425","1391–1425":"1391–1425","1419–1478":"1419–1478","1420–1490":"1420–1490","1423–1490":"1423–1490","1375–Male":"1375–Surnud","1375–Female":"1375–Surnud","1395":"1395","1490":"1490","1391":"1391","1425":"1425","about 1417":"umbes 1417","1423":"1423","1478":"1478","1420":"1420","about 1425":"umbes 1425","1375":"1375","about 1420":"umbes 1420","1419":"1419","about 1395":"umbes 1395","Wraxall Manor, South Wraxall, Wiltshire, England":"South Wraxall, Wiltshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom